{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Let's stop calling it \"Artificial Intelligence\" and call it what it is: \"a plagiarist\" because it does not create anything but copies existing works by existing creators and modifies them in such a way that it can escape copyright.",
    "This is the greatest theft of intellectual property ever recorded since the European settlers arrived in Native American lands\" states in his opinion article of New York Times in March 2023 [26].Conversely, what we perceive as NI seems to be a product of biological evolution, with the human brain serving as its \"Central Processing Unit\".",
    "Powered by the ATP (adenosine triphosphate) and ADP (adenosine diphosphate) cycle within our cells, the energy produced is transferred within the brain's 86 billion neurons, which in turn transmit electrochemical signals through synapses, enabling cognitive functions such as visualization and perception of the world-model we live in, attention to something important, short and long memory, language, and consciousness [27], a concept that we can barely understand or agree upon its formal definition.",
    "Unlike AI, NI does not produce results on deterministically pre-programmed algorithms but rather acts and constructs solutions intuitively, through preconceived notions, life experiences, incentives, sometimes irrationality, and continuous interactions with the environment; thus, formulating the properties of agency.To add more to the mystery of NI, a famous theory proposed by Penrose and Hameroff argues that human consciousness is nothing more than the collective collapse of the wavefunction that describes the quantum microstate of particles that move within microtubules.",
    "Microtubules are rigid hollow rods approximately 25 nm in diameter that are contained within our brain cells."
  ],
